### 1.5 Orbital Mechanics (Secondary Markets & Liquidity)
After the IPO, the company no longer receives your money. Cadets are simply trading existing shares among themselves. This is the Secondary Market, driven entirely by the brutal laws of Supply and Demand.

* The Order Book: A live, ticking list showing exactly what buyers are willing to pay (The Bid) and what sellers are demanding to receive (The Ask).
* Liquidity (Market Depth): How easy is it to buy or sell a stock without altering its price? 
  * High Liquidity: Large-caps have millions of buyers and sellers. You can sell ₹1 Crore of Reliance instantly without the price moving a single paisa.
  * Low Liquidity (The Trap): Obscure small-caps might only have a few buyers. If you try to sell a large block of shares, you will run out of buyers and the price will free-fall as your order executes. This is called "Slippage."
* Order Types:
  * ⚡ Market Order: "Buy this stock RIGHT NOW at whatever the lowest seller is asking." 
  * 🎯 Limit Order: "I will only buy this stock if the price drops to exactly ₹150."
  * 🛡️ Stop-Loss Order: "If the price drops to ₹90, trigger an automatic market sell order. Eject me from the ship to prevent total destruction."

