### 1.6 Cargo Drops (Corporate Actions)
Owning a piece of a company entitles you to specific corporate events authorized by the Board of Directors.

* Dividends (Profit Sharing): When a mature company makes massive excess profit, it doesn't always reinvest it. Instead, it drops raw cash directly into your bank account as a reward for holding the stock. (Note: The stock price usually drops by the exact amount of the dividend on the payout day).
* Stock Splits (Psychological Pricing): If a stock becomes too mathematically "heavy" (e.g., MRF trading at ₹1,00,000 per share), retail cadets can't afford a single share. The company might execute a "1-for-10 Split." If you owned 1 share at ₹1,00,000, you now own 10 shares worth ₹10,000 each. Your total value remains identical, but the stock is now highly accessible to new buyers.
* Bonus Shares: The company gives you free additional shares out of its accumulated cash reserves. Similar to a split, the stock price adjusts downward proportionally.

