### 1.8 Convoy Protocols (Mutual Funds vs. ETFs)
Flying a single ship (stock picking) is incredibly dangerous. If you put all your fuel into one ship and the CEO commits fraud, your account goes to zero. You must fly a "Convoy"—a single asset that holds dozens of different stocks to spread out your risk (Diversification).

* Active Mutual Funds: You give your money to a highly-paid human Fund Manager who tries to hand-pick the best stocks to beat the Nifty 50. 
  * The Tax: They charge high fees (Expense Ratios up to 2% per year). 
  * The Reality: Historically, 80% of human fund managers fail to beat the basic market index over a 10-year period because their fees eat their profits.
* Index Funds (Passive): A dumb, cheap computer algorithm that simply buys all the stocks in the Nifty 50 in their exact proportions. It charges almost nothing (Expense Ratio of 0.1%) and historically beats human managers over long time horizons. 
* ETFs (Exchange Traded Funds): An Index Fund that trades exactly like a stock. You can buy and sell it at any second during market hours. Traditional Mutual Funds only calculate their price (NAV - Net Asset Value) once at the end of the trading day.
* SIP (Systematic Investment Plan): The ultimate, emotionless wealth-building protocol. You automate your broker to buy ₹5,000 of an Index Fund every single month on the 1st, regardless of whether the market is crashing or booming. 
  * The Math: When the market is high, you buy fewer shares. When the market crashes, everything is on sale, and your ₹5,000 buys more shares. This mathematically lowers your average purchase price over time without requiring you to perfectly time the market.

> [AURA'S LOG] "Cadets who try to perfectly time the market usually fail. Cadets who set up an automated SIP into an Index Fund and do absolutely nothing for 20 years usually become millionaires. Time in the market > Timing the market."

